# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: archegonium
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] The **ABC model of flower development** is a scientific model of the process by which flowering plants produce a pattern of gene expression in meristems that leads to the appearance of an organ oriented towards sexual reproduction, a flower.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] The latter phase has been modelled using the **ABC model**, which aims to describe the biological basis of the process from the perspective of molecular and developmental genetics.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] An external stimulus is required in order to trigger the differentiation of the meristem into a flower meristem.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] This stimulus will activate mitotic cell division in the apical meristem, particularly on its sides where new primordia are formed.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] This same stimulus will also cause the meristem to follow a developmental pattern that will lead to the growth of floral meristems as opposed to vegetative meristems.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] The main difference between these two types of meristem, apart from the obvious disparity between the objective organ, is the verticillate (or whorled) phyllotaxis, that is, the absence of stem elongation among the successive whorls or verticils of the primordium.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] These verticils follow an acropetal development, giving rise to sepals, petals, stamens and carpels.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] Another difference from vegetative axillary meristems is that the floral meristem is "determined", which means that, once differentiated, its cells will no longer divide.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] The identity of the organs present in the four floral verticils is a consequence of the interaction of at least three types of gene products, each with distinct functions.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] According to the ABC model, functions A and C are required in order to determine the identity of the verticils of the perianth and the reproductive verticils, respectively.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] These functions are exclusive and the absence of one of them means that the other will determine the identity of all the floral verticils.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] The B function allows the differentiation of petals from sepals in the secondary verticil, as well as the differentiation of the stamen from the carpel on the tertiary verticil.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] Goethe's **foliar theory** was formulated in the 18th century and it suggests that the constituent parts of a flower are structurally modified leaves, which are functionally specialized for reproduction or protection.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] The transition from the vegetative phase to a reproductive phase involves a dramatic change in the plant's vital cycle, perhaps the most important one, as the process must be carried out correctly in order to guarantee that the plant produces descendants.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] This transition is characterised by the induction and development of the meristem of the inflorescence, which will produce a collection of flowers or one flower.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] This morphogenetic change contains both endogenous and exogenous elements: For example, in order for the change to be initiated the plant must have a certain number of leaves and contain a certain level of total biomass.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] Certain environmental conditions are also required such as a characteristic photoperiod.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] Plant hormones play an important part in the process, with the gibberellins having a particularly important role.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] There are many signals that regulate the molecular biology of the process.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] The following three genes in *Arabidopsis thaliana* possess both common and independent functions in floral transition: *FLOWERING LOCUS T* (*FT*), *LEAFY* (*LFY*), *SUPPRESSOR OF OVEREXPRESSION OF CONSTANS1* (*SOC1*, also called *AGAMOUS-LIKE20*).
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] *SOC1* is a MADS-box-type gene, which integrates responses to photoperiod, vernalization and gibberellins.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] The meristem can be defined as the tissue or group of plant tissues that contain undifferentiated stem cells, which are capable of producing any type of cell tissue.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] Their maintenance and development, both in the vegetative meristem or the meristem of the inflorescence is controlled by genetic cell fate determination mechanisms.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] This means that a number of genes will directly regulate, for example, the maintenance of the stem cell's characteristics (gene *WUSCHEL* or *WUS*), and others will act via negative feedback mechanisms in order to inhibit a characteristic (gene *CLAVATA* or *CLV*).
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] In this way both mechanisms give rise to a feedback loop, which along with other elements lend a great deal of robustness to the system.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] Along with the *WUS* gene the *SHOOTMERISTEMLESS* (*STM*) gene also represses the differentiation of the meristematic dome.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] This gene acts by inhibiting the possible differentiation of the stem cells but still allows cell division in the daughter cells, which, had they been allowed to differentiate, would have given rise to distinct organs.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] A flower's anatomy, as defined by the presence of a series of organs (sepals, petals, stamens and carpels) positioned according to a given pattern, facilitate sexual reproduction in flowering plants.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] The ABC model of flower development was first formulated by George Haughn and Chris Somerville in 1988.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] It was first used as a model to describe the collection of genetic mechanisms that establish floral organ identity in the Rosids, as exemplified by *Arabidopsis thaliana*, and the Asterids, as demonstrated by *Antirrhinum majus*.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] Both species have four verticils (sepals, petals, stamens and carpels), which are defined by the differential expression of a number of homeotic genes present in each verticil.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] This means that the sepals are solely characterized by the expression of A genes, while the petals are characterized by the co-expression of A and B genes.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] The B and C genes establish the identity of the stamens and the carpels only require C genes to be active.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] Type A and C genes are reciprocally antagonistic.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] The fact that these homeotic genes determine an organ's identity becomes evident when a gene that represents a particular function, for example the A gene, is not expressed.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Arabidopsis* this loss results in a flower which is composed of one verticil of carpels, another containing stamens and another of carpels.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] This method for studying gene function uses reverse genetics techniques to produce transgenic plants that contain a mechanism for gene silencing through RNA interference.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] In other studies, using forward genetics techniques such as genetic mapping, it is the analysis of the phenotypes of flowers with structural anomalies that leads to the cloning of the gene of interest.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] The flowers may possess a non-functional or over expressed allele for the gene being studied.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] The existence of two supplementary functions, D and E, have also been proposed in addition to the A, B and C functions already discussed.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] Function D specifies the identity of the ovule, as a separate reproductive function from the development of the carpels, which occurs after their determination.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] Function E relates to a physiological requirement that is a characteristic of all floral verticils, although, it was initially described as necessary for the development of the three innermost verticils (Function E *sensu stricto*).
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] However, its broader definition (*sensu lato*) suggests that it is required in the four verticils.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] The gene products of genes with D and E functions are also MADS-box genes.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] The methodology for studying flower development involves two steps.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] Firstly, the identification of the exact genes required for determining the identity of the floral meristem.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana* these include APETALA1 (*AP1*) and LEAFY (*LFY*).
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] Secondly, genetic analysis is carried out on the aberrant phenotypes for the relative characteristics of the flowers, which allows the characterization of the homeotic genes implicated in the process.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] There are a great many mutations that affect floral morphology, although the analysis of these mutants is a recent development.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] Supporting evidence for the existence of these mutations comes from the fact that a large number affect the identity of floral organs.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] For example, some organs develop in a location where others should develop.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] This is called homeotic mutation, which is analogous to HOX gene mutations found in *Drosophila*.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Arabidopsis* and *Antirrhinum*, the two taxa on which models are based, these mutations always affect adjacent verticils.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] Cloning studies have been carried out on DNA in the genes associated with the affected homeotic functions in the mutants discussed above.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] These studies used serial analysis of gene expression throughout floral development to show patterns of tissue expression, which, in general, correspond with the predictions of the ABC model.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] The nature of these genes corresponds to that of transcription factors, which, as expected, have analogous structures to a group of factors contained in yeasts and animal cells.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] This group is called MADS, which is an acronym for the different factors contained in the group.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] These MADS factors have been detected in all the vegetable species studied, although the involvement of other elements involved in the regulation of gene expression cannot be discounted.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana*, function A is mainly represented by two genes *APETALA1* (*AP1)* and *APETALA2* (*AP2*) *AP1* is a MADS-box type gene, while *AP2* belongs to the family of genes that contains AP2, which it gives its name to and which consists of transcription factors that are only found in plants.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] AP2 has also been shown to complex with the co-repressor TOPLESS (TPL) in developing floral buds to repress the C-class gene *AGAMOUS* (*AG*).
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] *AP2* not only functions in the first two verticils, but also in the remaining two, in developing ovules and even in leaves.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] It is also likely that post-transcriptional regulation exists, which controls its A function, or even that it has other purposes in the determination of organ identity independent of that mentioned here.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Antirrhinum*, the orthologous gene to *AP1* is *SQUAMOSA* (*SQUA*), which also has a particular impact on the floral meristem.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] The homologs for *AP2* are *LIPLESS1* (*LIP1*) and *LIPLESS2* (*LIP2*), which have a redundant function and are of special interest in the development of sepals, petals and ovules.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] A total of three genes have been isolated from *Petunia hybrida* that are similar to *AP2*: *P. hybrida APETALA2A* (*PhAP2A*), *PhAP2B* and *PhAP2C*.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] *PhAP2A* is, to a large degree, homologous with the *AP2* gene of *Arabidopsis*, both in its sequence and in its expression pattern, which suggests that the two genes are orthologs.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] The proteins *PhAP2B* and *PhAP2C*, on the other hand, are slightly different, even though they belong to the family of transcription factors that are similar to *AP2*.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] In addition they are expressed in different ways, although they are very similar in comparison with *PhAP2A*.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] In fact, the mutants for these genes do not show the usual phenotype, that of the null alleles of A genes.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana* the type-B function mainly arises from two genes, *APETALA3* (*AP3*) and *PISTILLATA* (*PI*), both of which are MADS-box genes.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] A mutation of either of these genes causes the homeotic conversion of petals into sepals and of stamens into carpels.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] This also occurs in its orthologs in *A. majus*, which are DEFICIENS (*DEF*) and *GLOBOSA* (*GLO*) respectively.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] For both species the active form of binding with DNA is that derived from the heterodimer: AP3 and PI, or DEF and GLO, dimerize.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] This is the form in which they are able to function.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] The *GLO*/*PI* lines that have been duplicated in *Petunia* contain *P. hybrida GLOBOSA1* (*PhGLO1*, also called *FBP1*) and also *PhGLO2* (also called *PMADS2* or *FBP3*).
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] For the functional elements equivalent to *AP3*/*DEF* in *Petunia* there is both a gene that possesses a relatively similar sequence, called *PhDEF* and there is also an atypical B function gene called PhTM6.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] Phylogenetic studies have placed the first three within the «euAP3» lineage, while PhTM6 belongs to that of «paleoAP3».
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] As discussed above, the floral organs of eudicotyledonous angiosperms are arranged in 4 different verticils, containing the sepals, petals, stamen and carpels.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] The ABC model states that the identity of these organs is determined by the homeotic genes A, A+B, B+C and C, respectively.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] In contrast with the sepal and petal verticils of the eudicots, the perigone of many plants of the family Liliaceae have two nearly identical external petaloid verticils (the tepals).
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] In order to explain the floral morphology of the Liliaceae, van Tunen *et al.* proposed a modified ABC model in 1993.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] This model suggests that class B genes are not only expressed in verticils 2 and 3, but also in 1.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] It therefore follows that the organs of verticils 1 and 2 express class A and B genes and this is how they have a petaloid structure.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] This theoretical model has been experimentally proven through the cloning and characterization of homologs of the *Antirrhinum* genes *GLOBOSA* and *DEFICIENS* in a Liliaceae, the tulip *Tulipa gesneriana*.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are expressed in verticils 1,2 and 3.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] The homologs *GLOBOSA* and *DEFICIENS* have also been isolated and characterized in *Agapanthus praecox* ssp.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] *orientalis* (Agapanthaceae), which is phylogenetically distant from the model organisms.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] In this study the genes were called *ApGLO* and *ApDEF*, respectively.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] Both contain open reading frames that code for proteins with 210 to 214 amino acids.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] Phylogenetic analysis of these sequences indicated that they belong to B gene family of the monocotyledons.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] In situ hybridization studies revealed that both sequences are expressed in verticil 1 as well as in 2 and 3.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] When taken together, these observations show that the floral development mechanism of *Agapanthus* also follows the modified ABC model.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana*, the C function is derived from one MADS-box type gene called *AGAMOUS* (*AG*), which intervenes both in the establishment of stamen and carpel identity as well as in the determination of the floral meristem.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] Therefore, the *AG* mutants are devoid of androecium and gynoecium and they have petals and sepals in their place.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] In addition, the growth in the centre of the flower is undifferentiated, therefore the petals and sepals grow in repetitive verticils.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] The *PLENA* (*PLE*) gene is present in *A. majus*, in place of the *AG* gene, although it is not an ortholog.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] However, the *FARINELLI* (*FAR*) gene is an ortholog, which is specific to the development of the anthers and the maturation of pollen.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Petunia*, *Antirrhinum* and in maize the C function is controlled by a number of genes that act in the same manner.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] The genes that are closer homologs of *AG* in *Petunia* are *pMADS3* and *floral-binding protein 6* (*FBP6*).
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] The D function genes were discovered in 1995.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are MADS-box proteins and they have a function that is distinct from those previously described, although they have a certain homology with C function genes.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are called *FLORAL BINDING PROTEIN7* (*FBP7*) and *FLORAL BINDING PROTEIN1L* (*FBP1l*).
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] It was found that, in *Petunia*, they are involved in the development of the ovule.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] Equivalent genes were later found in *Arabidopsis*, where they are also involved in controlling the development of carpels and the ovule and even with structures related to seed dispersal.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] The appearance of interesting phenotypes in RNA interference studies in *Petunia* and tomato led, in 1994, to the definition of a new type of function in the floral development model.
[src:archegonium/abc-model-of-flower-development] The E function was initially thought to be only involved in the development of the three innermost verticils, however, subsequent work found that its expression was required in all the floral verticils.
[src:archegonium/aestivation-botany] Aestivation can be an important taxonomic diagnostic; for example Malvaceae flower buds have valvate sepals, with the exception of the genera *Fremontodendron* and *Chiranthodendron*, which have sometimes been misplaced as a result.
[src:archegonium/aestivation-botany] The terms used to describe aestivation are the same as those used to describe leaf vernation.
[src:archegonium/agronomy] This topic of agronomy involves selective breeding of plants to produce the best crops for various conditions.
[src:archegonium/agronomy] Plant breeding has increased crop yields and has improved the nutritional value of numerous crops, including corn, soybeans, and wheat.
[src:archegonium/agronomy] It has also resulted in the development of new types of plants.
[src:archegonium/agronomy] For example, a hybrid grain named triticale was produced by crossbreeding rye and wheat.
[src:archegonium/agronomy] Triticale contains more usable protein than does either rye or wheat.
[src:archegonium/agronomy] Agronomy has also been instrumental for fruit and vegetable production research.
[src:archegonium/agronomy] Furthermore, the application of plant breeding for turfgrass development has resulted in a reduction in the demand for fertilizer and water inputs (requirements), as well as turf-types with higher disease resistance.
[src:archegonium/agronomy] Agronomists use biotechnology to extend and expedite the development of desired characteristics.
[src:archegonium/agronomy] Biotechnology is often a laboratory activity requiring field testing of new crop varieties that are developed.
[src:archegonium/agronomy] In addition to increasing crop yields agronomic biotechnology is being applied increasingly for novel uses other than food.
[src:archegonium/agronomy] For example, oilseed is at present used mainly for margarine and other food oils, but it can be modified to produce fatty acids for detergents, substitute fuels and petrochemicals.
[src:archegonium/agronomy] Agronomists study sustainable ways to make soils more productive and profitable.
[src:archegonium/agronomy] They classify soils and analyze them to determine whether they contain nutrients vital for plant growth.
[src:archegonium/agronomy] Common macronutrients analyzed include compounds of nitrogen, phosphorus, potassium, calcium, magnesium, and sulfur.
[src:archegonium/agronomy] Soil is also assessed for several micronutrients, like zinc and boron.
[src:archegonium/agronomy] The percentage of organic matter, soil pH, and nutrient holding capacity (cation exchange capacity) are tested in a regional laboratory.
[src:archegonium/agronomy] Agronomists will interpret these laboratory reports and make recommendations to modify soil nutrients for optimal plant growth.
[src:archegonium/agronomy] Additionally, agronomists develop methods to preserve soil and decrease the effects of [erosion] by wind and water.
[src:archegonium/agronomy] For example, a technique known as contour plowing may be used to prevent soil erosion and conserve rainfall.
[src:archegonium/agronomy] Researchers of agronomy also seek ways to use the soil more effectively for solving other problems.
[src:archegonium/agronomy] Such problems include the disposal of human and animal manure, water pollution, and pesticide accumulation in the soil, as well as preserving the soil for future generations such as the burning of paddocks after crop production.
[src:archegonium/agronomy] Pasture management techniques include no-till farming, planting of soil-binding grasses along contours on steep slopes, and using contour drains of depths as much as 1 metre.
[src:archegonium/agronomy] Agroecology is the management of agricultural systems with an emphasis on ecological and environmental applications.
[src:archegonium/agronomy] This topic is associated closely with work for sustainable agriculture, organic farming, and alternative food systems and the development of alternative cropping systems.
[src:archegonium/agronomy] Theoretical production ecology is the quantitative study of the growth of crops.
[src:archegonium/agronomy] The plant is treated as a kind of biological factory, which processes light, carbon dioxide, water, and nutrients into harvestable products.
[src:archegonium/agronomy] The main parameters are temperature, sunlight, standing crop biomass, plant production distribution, and nutrient and water supply.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] The aleurone layer surrounds the endosperm tissue of grass seeds and is morphologically and biochemically distinct from it.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] Starchy endosperm cells are large, irregularly shaped cells and contain starch grains while aleurone cells are cuboidal in shape and contain aleurone grains.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] In most cultivated cereals (wheat species, rye, oats, rice and maize) the aleurone is single-layered, whereas barley has a multicellular aleurone layer.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] Thick primary cell walls enclose and protect the aleurone cells.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] The aleurone layer is important for both the developing seed and the mature plant.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] The aleurone tissue accumulates large quantities of oils and lipids that are useful during seed development.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] It is also a site of mineral storage and in some species, functions in seed dormancy.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] The aleurone may also express several pathogen-protective proteins including PR-4.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] Aleurone also serves as the most dietarily beneficial fraction in many brans.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] In addition, the aleurone tissue contains many protein-storing vacuoles known as protein bodies.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] In cereals with starchy endosperm, the aleurone contains about 30% of the kernel's proteins.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] In multicolored corn, anthocyanin pigments in the aleurone layer give the kernels a dark, bluish-black color.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] Aleurone proteins can have two different morphological features, homogenous and heterogeneous.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] The homogenous aleurone consists of similar protein bodies (e.g.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] *Phaseolus vulgaris*) while the heterogeneous aleurone consists of granules of different shapes and types of proteins covered with a membrane (e.g.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] The development of the aleurone layer involves several periclinal, and anticlinal cell divisions and several steps of genetic regulation.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] The *dek1* gene and *crinkly4 (cr4)* kinase both function as positive regulators of aleurone cell fate.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] The normal *dek1* gene is needed in order to receive and respond to positional cues that determine the fate of aleurone cells during development.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] Mutants of the *dek1* gene block the formation of aleurone and cause the cells to develop as starchy endosperm cells instead of aleurone cells.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] This causes the seed to lack an aleurone layer.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] This mutation is caused by the insertion of a *Mu* transposon into the *dek1* gene, causing it to function incorrectly.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] However, this transposon may sometimes remove itself from the gene, restoring the function of *dek1*.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] Experiments in this area have helped demonstrate that the cues that determine aleurone positioning are still present in the later stages of development, and the aleurone cells still respond to these cues.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] Similar to the *dek1* mutation, genes with a mutation in the *cr4* gene also cause a switch in the fate of aleurone cells.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] The *cr4* gene codes for a receptor kinase and so is involved in signal transduction pathways involving the fate of aleurone cells.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] Plants with a mutated *cr4* gene are shorter than normal and produce crinkled leaves.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] In addition, several hormones influence the development of the aleurone layer, including auxin, cytokinin, abscisic acid (ABA), and gibberellin (GA).
[src:archegonium/aleurone] Auxin and cytokinin play a role in the earlier stages of aleurone development.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] The maturation of aleurone is promoted by ABA while germination is promoted by GA.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] The aleurone layer performs a variety of functions to help maintain proper development of the seed.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] One example of this is maintaining a low pH in the apoplast.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] In cereals, the aleurone layer releases organic and phosphoric acids in order to keep the pH of the endosperm between a pH of 3.5 and 4.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] In barley, the aleurone layer also releases nitrite into the starchy endosperm and apoplast under anaerobic conditions.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] In addition, although the function is unclear, a certain class of hemoglobins is present in the outer layer of living cells including the aleurone tissue in barley and rice seeds.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] During seed germination, the plant embryo produces the hormone gibberellin which triggers the aleurone cells to release α-amylase for the hydrolysis of starch, proteases, and storage proteins into the endosperm.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] Evidence that G-proteins play a role in the gibberellin signaling events has been obtained.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] The breakdown of the starchy endosperm supplies sugars to drive the growth of roots and the acrospire.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] This release of amylase is considered to be the most important and sole function of the aleurone layer.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] This effect is inhibited by the plant hormone abscisic acid, which keeps the seed dormant.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] After completing this function, the aleurone cells in the developing seed undergo apoptosis.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] Experiments conducted in the 1960s confirmed that in order for the aleurone layer to secrete starch-degrading enzymes, the embryo must be present.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] Following removal of the embryo, starch-degrading enzymes were not released and no degradation of the starch tissue occurred.
[src:archegonium/aleurone] The gibberellin effect on the aleurone is used in brewing, specifically in the production of barley malt where treatment ensures that a batch of barley seeds will germinate evenly.
[src:archegonium/algae] Algae are polyphyletic as they have multiple evolutionary origins.
[src:archegonium/algae] Although algae with two-membraned chloroplasts seem to form a paraphyletic group within the clade Archaeplastida, other algae with chloroplasts that have three or more membranes evolved from protists that acquired photosynthesis after engulfing archaeplastids.
[src:archegonium/algae] Most algae are single-celled organisms without roots, leaves, or stems.
[src:archegonium/algae] Most are photoautotrophs and the main primary producers of aquatic ecosystems, although some are mixotrophs that derive metabolic energy both from internal photosynthesis and from foraging external nutrients.
[src:archegonium/algae] Some unicellular algae have become heterotrophs or parasites, relying entirely on external energy sources.
[src:archegonium/algae] Algae have photosynthetic machinery ultimately derived from cyanobacteria that produce oxygen by splitting water molecules, unlike photosynthetic bacteria.
[src:archegonium/algae] Fossilized filamentous algae from the Vindhya basin have been dated to 1.6 to 1.7 billion years ago.
[src:archegonium/algae] Because of the wide range of types of algae, there is a correspondingly wide range of industrial and traditional applications in human society.
[src:archegonium/algae] Traditional seaweed farming practices have existed for thousands of years and have strong traditions in East Asian food cultures.
[src:archegonium/algae] More modern algaculture applications extend the food traditions for other applications, including cattle feed, using algae for bioremediation or pollution control, transforming sunlight into algae fuels or other chemicals used in industrial processes, and in medical and scientific applications.
[src:archegonium/algae] The singular *alga* is the Latin word for "seaweed" and retains that meaning in English.
[src:archegonium/algae] Although some speculate that it is related to Latin *algēre*, "be cold", no reason is known to associate seaweed with temperature.
[src:archegonium/algae] A more likely source is *alliga*, "binding, entwining".
[src:archegonium/algae] The Ancient Greek word for "seaweed" was φῦκος (*phŷkos*), which could mean either the seaweed (probably red algae) or a red dye derived from it.
[src:archegonium/algae] The Latinization, *fūcus*, meant primarily the cosmetic rouge.
[src:archegonium/algae] The etymology is uncertain, but a strong candidate has long been some word related to the Biblical פוך (*pūk*), "paint" (if not that word itself), a cosmetic eye-shadow used by the Ancient Egyptians and other inhabitants of the eastern Mediterranean.
[src:archegonium/algae] It could be any color: black, red, green, or blue.
[src:archegonium/algae] The study of algae is most commonly called phycology (from Greek *phykos* 'seaweed'); the term algology is falling out of use.
[src:archegonium/algae] The algae are a heterogeneous group of mostly photosynthetic organisms that produce oxygen and lack the reproductive features and structural complexity of land plants.
[src:archegonium/algae] This concept includes the cyanobacteria, which are prokaryotes, and all photosynthetic protists, which are eukaryotes.
[src:archegonium/algae] They contain chlorophyll *a* as their primary photosynthetic pigment, and generally inhabit aquatic environments.
[src:archegonium/algae] However, there are many exceptions to this definition.
[src:archegonium/algae] Many non-photosynthetic protists are included in the study of algae, such as the heterotrophic relatives of euglenophytes or the numerous species of colorless algae that have lost their chlorophyll during evolution (e.g., *Prototheca*).
[src:archegonium/algae] Some exceptional species of algae tolerate dry terrestrial habitats, such as soil, rocks, or caves hidden from light sources, although they still need enough moisture to become active.
[src:archegonium/algae] A range of algal morphologies is exhibited, and convergence of features in unrelated groups is common.
[src:archegonium/algae] The only groups to exhibit three-dimensional multicellular thalli are the reds and browns, and some chlorophytes.
[src:archegonium/algae] Apical growth is constrained to subsets of these groups: the florideophyte reds, various browns, and the charophytes.
[src:archegonium/algae] The form of charophytes is quite different from those of reds and browns, because they have distinct nodes, separated by internode 'stems'; whorls of branches reminiscent of the horsetails occur at the nodes.
[src:archegonium/algae] Conceptacles are another polyphyletic trait; they appear in the coralline algae and the Hildenbrandiales, as well as the browns.
[src:archegonium/algae] Most of the simpler algae are unicellular flagellates or amoeboids, but colonial and nonmotile forms have developed independently among several of the groups.
[src:archegonium/algae] In three lines, even higher levels of organization have been reached, with full tissue differentiation.
[src:archegonium/algae] These are the brown algae,—some of which may reach 50 m in length (kelps)—the red algae, and the green algae.
[src:archegonium/algae] The most complex forms are found among the charophyte algae (see Charales and Charophyta), in a lineage that eventually led to the higher land plants.
[src:archegonium/algae] The innovation that defines these nonalgal plants is the presence of female reproductive organs with protective cell layers that protect the zygote and developing embryo.
[src:archegonium/algae] Hence, the land plants are referred to as the Embryophytes.
[src:archegonium/algae] The term algal turf is commonly used but poorly defined.
[src:archegonium/algae] Algal turfs are thick, carpet-like beds of seaweed that retain sediment and compete with foundation species like corals and kelps, and they are usually less than 15 cm tall.
[src:archegonium/algae] Such a turf may consist of one or more species, and will generally cover an area in the order of a square metre or more.
[src:archegonium/algae] Many algae, particularly species of the Characeae, have served as model experimental organisms to understand the mechanisms of the water permeability of membranes, osmoregulation, salt tolerance, cytoplasmic streaming, and the generation of action potentials.
[src:archegonium/algae] Plant hormones are found not only in higher plants, but in algae, too.
[src:archegonium/algae] Rhodophyta, Chlorophyta, and Heterokontophyta, the three main algal divisions, have life cycles which show considerable variation and complexity.
[src:archegonium/algae] In general, an asexual phase exists where the seaweed's cells are diploid, a sexual phase where the cells are haploid, followed by fusion of the male and female gametes.
[src:archegonium/algae] Asexual reproduction permits efficient population increases, but less variation is possible.
[src:archegonium/algae] Commonly, in sexual reproduction of unicellular and colonial algae, two specialized, sexually compatible, haploid gametes make physical contact and fuse to form a zygote.
[src:archegonium/algae] To ensure a successful mating, the development and release of gametes is highly synchronized and regulated; pheromones may play a key role in these processes.
[src:archegonium/algae] Sexual reproduction allows for more variation and provides the benefit of efficient recombinational repair of DNA damage during meiosis, a key stage of the sexual cycle.
[src:archegonium/algae] However, sexual reproduction is more costly than asexual reproduction.
[src:archegonium/algae] Meiosis has been shown to occur in many different species of algae.
[src:archegonium/algae] Linnaeus, in *Species Plantarum* (1753), the starting point for modern botanical nomenclature, recognized 14 genera of algae, of which only four are currently considered among algae.
[src:archegonium/algae] In *Systema Naturae*, Linnaeus described the genera *Volvox* and *Corallina*, and a species of *Acetabularia* (as *Madrepora*), among the animals.
[src:archegonium/algae] In 1768, Samuel Gottlieb Gmelin (1744–1774) published the *Historia Fucorum*, the first work dedicated to marine algae and the first book on marine biology to use the then new binomial nomenclature of Linnaeus.
[src:archegonium/algae] It included elaborate illustrations of seaweed and marine algae on folded leaves.
[src:archegonium/algae] Harvey (1811–1866) and Lamouroux (1813) were the first to divide macroscopic algae into four divisions based on their pigmentation.
[src:archegonium/algae] This is the first use of a biochemical criterion in plant systematics.
[src:archegonium/algae] Harvey's four divisions are: red algae (Rhodospermae), brown algae (Melanospermae), green algae (Chlorospermae), and Diatomaceae.
[src:archegonium/algae] At this time, microscopic algae were discovered and reported by a different group of workers (e.g., O.
[src:archegonium/algae] Müller and Ehrenberg) studying the Infusoria (microscopic organisms).
[src:archegonium/algae] Unlike macroalgae, which were clearly viewed as plants, microalgae were frequently considered animals because they are often motile.
[src:archegonium/algae] Even the nonmotile (coccoid) microalgae were sometimes merely seen as stages of the lifecycle of plants, macroalgae, or animals.
[src:archegonium/algae] Although used as a taxonomic category in some pre-Darwinian classifications, e.g., Linnaeus (1753), de Jussieu (1789), Lamouroux (1813), Harvey (1836), Horaninow (1843), Agassiz (1859), Wilson & Cassin (1864), in further classifications, the "algae" are seen as an artificial, polyphyletic group.
[src:archegonium/algae] Throughout the 20th century, most classifications treated the following groups as divisions or classes of algae: cyanophytes, rhodophytes, chrysophytes, xanthophytes, bacillariophytes, phaeophytes, pyrrhophytes (cryptophytes and dinophytes), euglenophytes, and chlorophytes.
[src:archegonium/algae] With the abandonment of plant-animal dichotomous classification, most groups of algae (sometimes all) were included in Protista, later also abandoned in favour of Eukaryota.
[src:archegonium/algae] However, as a legacy of the older plant life scheme, some groups that were also treated as protozoans in the past still have duplicated classifications (see ambiregnal protists).
[src:archegonium/algae] In other cases, some groups were originally characterized as parasitic algae (e.g., *Chlorochytrium*), but later were seen as endophytic algae.
[src:archegonium/algae] Some filamentous bacteria (e.g., *Beggiatoa*) were originally seen as algae.
[src:archegonium/algae] Furthermore, groups like the apicomplexans are also parasites derived from ancestors that possessed plastids, but are not included in any group traditionally seen as algae.
[src:archegonium/algae] The most recent estimate (as of January 2024) documents 50,605 living and 10,556 fossil algal species, according to the online database AlgaeBase.
[src:archegonium/algae] They are classified into 15 phyla or divisions.
[src:archegonium/algae] Some phyla are not photosynthetic, namely Picophyta and Rhodelphidophyta, but they are included in the database due to their close relationship with red algae.
[src:archegonium/algae] The various algal phyla can be differentiated according to several biological traits.
[src:archegonium/algae] They have distinct morphologies, photosynthetic pigmentation, storage products, cell wall composition, and mechanisms of carbon concentration.
[src:archegonium/algae] Some phyla have unique cellular structures.
[src:archegonium/algae] , the most common genus of cyanobacteria.
[src:archegonium/algae] Among prokaryotes, five major groups of bacteria have evolved the ability to photosynthesize, including heliobacteria, green sulfur and nonsulfur bacteria and proteobacteria.
[src:archegonium/algae] However, the only lineage where oxygenic photosynthesis has evolved is in the cyanobacteria, often known as blue-green algae for their blue-green (cyan) coloration.
[src:archegonium/algae] They are classified as the phylum Cyanobacteriota or Cyanophyta.
[src:archegonium/algae] However, this phylum also includes two classes of non-photosynthetic bacteria: Melainabacteria (also called Vampirovibrionia or Vampirovibrionophyceae) and Sericytochromatia (also known as Blackallbacteria).
[src:archegonium/algae] A third class contains the photosynthetic ones, known as Cyanophyceae (also called Cyanobacteriia or Oxyphotobacteria).
[src:archegonium/algae] As bacteria, their cells lack membrane-bound organelles, with the exception of thylakoids.
[src:archegonium/algae] Like other algae, cyanobacteria have chlorophyll *a* as their primary photosynthetic pigment.
[src:archegonium/algae] Their accessory pigments include phycobilins (phycoerythrobilin and phycocyanobilin), carotenoids and, in some cases, *b*, *d*, or *f* chlorophylls, generally distributed in phycobilisomes found in the surface of thylakoids.
[src:archegonium/algae] They display a variety of body forms, such as single cells, colonies, and unbranched or branched filaments.
[src:archegonium/algae] Their cells are commonly covered in a sheath of mucilage, and they also have a typical gram-negative bacterial cell wall composed largely of peptidoglycan.
[src:archegonium/algae] They have various storage particles, including cyanophycin as aminoacid and nitrogen reserves, "cyanophycean starch" (similar to plant amylose) for carbohydrates, and lipid droplets.
[src:archegonium/algae] Their Rubisco enzymes are concentrated in carboxysomes.
[src:archegonium/algae] They occupy a diverse array of aquatic and terrestrial habitats, including extreme environments from hot springs to polar glaciers.
[src:archegonium/algae] Some are subterranean, living via hydrogen-based lithoautotrophy instead of photosynthesis.
[src:archegonium/algae] Three lineages of cyanobacteria, *Prochloraceae*, *Prochlorothrix* and *Prochlorococcus*, independently evolved to have chlorophylls *a* and *b* instead of phycobilisomes.
[src:archegonium/algae] Due to their different pigmentation, they were historically grouped in a separate division, Prochlorophyta, as this is the typical pigmentation seen in green algae (e.g., chlorophytes).
[src:archegonium/algae] Eventually, this classification became obsolete, as it is a polyphyletic grouping.
[src:archegonium/algae] Cyanobacteria are included as algae by most phycological sources and by the International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants, although a few authors exclude them from the definition of algae and reserve the term for eukaryotes only.
[src:archegonium/algae] Eukaryotic algae contain chloroplasts that are similar in structure to cyanobacteria.
[src:archegonium/algae] Chloroplasts contain circular DNA like that in cyanobacteria and are interpreted as representing reduced endosymbiotic cyanobacteria.
[src:archegonium/algae] However, the exact origin of the chloroplasts is different among separate lineages of algae, reflecting their acquisition during different endosymbiotic events.
[src:archegonium/algae] Many groups contain some members that are no longer photosynthetic.
[src:archegonium/algae] Some retain plastids, but not chloroplasts, while others have lost plastids entirely.
[src:archegonium/algae] Primary algae are those with "primary chloroplasts", i.e. chloroplasts with two membranes, evolved through a single symbiogenetic event with an endosymbiont β-cyanobacterium as early as 1.6 Gya during the Mesoproterozoic.
[src:archegonium/algae] These algae are mainly grouped in the clade Archaeplastida (meaning "ancient plastid"), which includes the major groups Viridiplantae (green algae *sensu lato* and all land plants) and Rhodophyta (red algae) as well as the minor group Glaucophyta (grey algae).
[src:archegonium/algae] Land plants (embryophytes) are pigmented similarly to green algae and likely evolved from the freshwater green algae clade Streptophyta, which is sister taxon to Chlorophyta (green algae *sensu stricto*) and the basal clade Prasinodermophyta.
[src:archegonium/algae] There is also a minor group of amoeboid protists with primary plastids evolved via different origin and at a much later date than archaeplastid chloroplasts.
[src:archegonium/algae] The four species of the euglyphid amoebae genus *Paulinella*, have cyanobionts (known as cyanelles) that perform photosynthesis, likely originated from the endosymbiosis of a α-cyanobacterium (probably an ancestral member of Chroococcales), about 90–140 Mya during the Cretaceous.
[src:archegonium/algae] Secondary algae are eukaryotes with "secondary chloroplasts", i.e. those evolved from phagocytosis and subsequent endosymbiosis of primary algae (mainly green or red algae) or other secondary algae, thus "stealing" the endosymbionts' photosynthetic capability.
[src:archegonium/algae] As a result, these algae have chloroplasts surrounded by three or more membranes, and appeared independently in various distantly related protist lineages.
[src:archegonium/algae] Two lineages of secondary algae, chlorarachniophytes and euglenophytes have "green" chloroplasts containing chlorophylls *a* and *b*.
[src:archegonium/algae] Their chloroplasts are surrounded by four and three membranes, respectively, and were probably retained from ingested green algae.
[src:archegonium/algae] Other groups have "red" chloroplasts containing chlorophylls *a* and *c*, and phycobilins.
[src:archegonium/algae] The shape can vary; they may be of discoid, plate-like, reticulate, cup-shaped, spiral, or ribbon shaped.
[src:archegonium/algae] They have one or more pyrenoids to preserve protein and starch.
[src:archegonium/algae] The latter chlorophyll type is not known from any prokaryotes or primary chloroplasts, but genetic similarities with red algae suggest a relationship there.
[src:archegonium/algae] The typical dinoflagellate chloroplast has three membranes, but considerable diversity exists in chloroplasts within the group, and a number of endosymbiotic events apparently occurred.
[src:archegonium/algae] The Apicomplexa, a group of closely related parasites, also have plastids called apicoplasts, which are not photosynthetic.
[src:archegonium/algae] The Chromerida are the closest relatives of apicomplexans, and some have retained their chloroplasts.
[src:archegonium/algae] The three alveolate groups evolved from a common myzozoan ancestor that obtained chloroplasts.
[src:archegonium/algae] The distribution of algal species has been fairly well studied since the founding of phytogeography in the mid-19th century.
[src:archegonium/algae] Algae spread mainly by the dispersal of spores analogously to the dispersal of cryptogamic plants by spores.
[src:archegonium/algae] Spores can be found in a variety of environments: fresh and marine waters, air, soil, and in or on other organisms.
[src:archegonium/algae] Whether a spore is to grow into an adult organism depends on the species and the environmental conditions where the spore lands.
[src:archegonium/algae] The spores of freshwater algae are dispersed mainly by running water and wind, as well as by living carriers.
[src:archegonium/algae] However, not all bodies of water can carry all species of algae, as the chemical composition of certain water bodies limits the algae that can survive within them.
[src:archegonium/algae] Marine spores are often spread by ocean currents.
[src:archegonium/algae] Ocean water presents many vastly different habitats based on temperature and nutrient availability, resulting in phytogeographic zones, regions, and provinces.
[src:archegonium/algae] To some degree, the distribution of algae is subject to floristic discontinuities caused by geographical features, such as Antarctica, long distances of ocean or general land masses.
[src:archegonium/algae] It is, therefore, possible to identify species occurring by locality, such as "Pacific algae" or "North Sea algae".
[src:archegonium/algae] When they occur out of their localities, hypothesizing a transport mechanism is usually possible, such as the hulls of ships.
[src:archegonium/algae] For example, *Ulva reticulata* and *U. fasciata* travelled from the mainland to Hawaii in this manner.
[src:archegonium/algae] Mapping is possible for select species only: "there are many valid examples of confined distribution patterns." For example, *Clathromorphum* is an arctic genus and is not mapped far south of there.
[src:archegonium/algae] For example, according to one standard textbook, in the British Isles, the *UK Biodiversity Steering Group Report* estimated there to be 20,000 algal species in the UK.
[src:archegonium/algae] Another checklist reports only about 5,000 species.
[src:archegonium/algae] and so on, but lacking any scientific basis or reliable sources, these numbers have no more credibility than the British ones mentioned above.
[src:archegonium/algae] Most estimates also omit microscopic algae, such as phytoplankton.
[src:archegonium/algae] Algae are prominent in bodies of water, common in terrestrial environments, and are found in unusual environments, such as on snow and ice.
[src:archegonium/algae] Seaweeds grow mostly in shallow marine waters, less than 100 m (330 ft) deep; however, some such as *Navicula pennata* have been recorded to a depth of 360 m (1,180 ft).
[src:archegonium/algae] A type of algae, *Ancylonema nordenskioeldii*, was found in Greenland in areas known as the 'Dark Zone', which caused an increase in the rate of melting ice sheet.
[src:archegonium/algae] The same algae was found in the Italian Alps, after pink ice appeared on parts of the Presena glacier.
[src:archegonium/algae] The various sorts of algae play significant roles in aquatic ecology.
[src:archegonium/algae] Microscopic forms that live suspended in the water column (phytoplankton) provide the food base for most marine food chains.
[src:archegonium/algae] In very high densities (algal blooms), these algae may discolor the water and outcompete, poison, or asphyxiate other life forms.
[src:archegonium/algae] Algae can be used as indicator organisms to monitor pollution in various aquatic systems.
[src:archegonium/algae] In many cases, algal metabolism is sensitive to various pollutants.
[src:archegonium/algae] Due to this, the species composition of algal populations may shift in the presence of chemical pollutants.
[src:archegonium/algae] To detect these changes, algae can be sampled from the environment and maintained in laboratories with relative ease.
[src:archegonium/algae] Some species of algae form symbiotic relationships with other organisms.
[src:archegonium/algae] In these symbioses, the algae supply photosynthates (organic substances) to the host organism providing protection to the algal cells.
[src:archegonium/algae] The host organism derives some or all of its energy requirements from the algae.
[src:archegonium/algae] Lichens are defined by the International Association for Lichenology to be "an association of a fungus and a photosynthetic symbiont resulting in a stable vegetative body having a specific structure".
[src:archegonium/algae] The fungi, or mycobionts, are mainly from the Ascomycota with a few from the Basidiomycota.
[src:archegonium/algae] In nature, they do not occur separate from lichens.
[src:archegonium/algae] It is unknown when they began to associate.
[src:archegonium/algae] One or more mycobiont associates with the same phycobiont species, from the green algae, except that alternatively, the mycobiont may associate with a species of cyanobacteria (hence "photobiont" is the more accurate term).
[src:archegonium/algae] A photobiont may be associated with many different mycobionts or may live independently; accordingly, lichens are named and classified as fungal species.
[src:archegonium/algae] The association is termed a morphogenesis because the lichen has a form and capabilities not possessed by the symbiont species alone (they can be experimentally isolated).
[src:archegonium/algae] The photobiont possibly triggers otherwise latent genes in the mycobiont.
[src:archegonium/algae] Trentepohlia is an example of a common green alga genus worldwide that can grow on its own or be lichenised.
[src:archegonium/algae] Lichen thus share some of the habitat and often similar appearance with specialized species of algae (*aerophytes*) growing on exposed surfaces such as tree trunks and rocks and sometimes discoloring them.
[src:archegonium/algae] Coral reefs are accumulated from the calcareous exoskeletons of marine invertebrates of the order Scleractinia (stony corals).
[src:archegonium/algae] These animals metabolize sugar and oxygen to obtain energy for their cell-building processes, including secretion of the exoskeleton, with water and carbon dioxide as byproducts.
[src:archegonium/algae] Dinoflagellates (algal protists) are often endosymbionts in the cells of the coral-forming marine invertebrates, where they accelerate host-cell metabolism by generating sugar and oxygen immediately available through photosynthesis using incident light and the carbon dioxide produced by the host.
[src:archegonium/algae] Reef-building stony corals (hermatypic corals) require endosymbiotic algae from the genus *Symbiodinium* to be in a healthy condition.
[src:archegonium/algae] The loss of *Symbiodinium* from the host is known as coral bleaching, a condition which leads to the deterioration of a reef.
[src:archegonium/algae] Endosymbiontic green algae live close to the surface of some sponges, for example, breadcrumb sponges (*Halichondria panicea*).
[src:archegonium/algae] The alga is thus protected from predators; the sponge is provided with oxygen and sugars which can account for 50 to 80% of sponge growth in some species.
[src:archegonium/algae] Prokaryotic algae, i.e., cyanobacteria, are the only group of organisms where oxygenic photosynthesis has evolved.
[src:archegonium/algae] The oldest undisputed fossil evidence of cyanobacteria is dated at 2100 million years ago, although stromatolites, associated with cyanobacterial biofilms, appear as early as 3500 million years ago in the fossil record.
[src:archegonium/algae] Eukaryotic algae are polyphyletic thus their origin cannot be traced back to a single hypothetical common ancestor.
[src:archegonium/algae] It is thought that they came into existence when photosynthetic coccoid cyanobacteria got phagocytized by a unicellular heterotrophic eukaryote (a protist), giving rise to double-membranous primary plastids.
[src:archegonium/algae] Such symbiogenic events (primary symbiogenesis) are believed to have occurred more than 1.5 billion years ago during the Calymmian period, early in Boring Billion, but it is difficult to track the key events because of so much time gap.
[src:archegonium/algae] This process of serial cell "capture" and "enslavement" explains the diversity of photosynthetic eukaryotes.
[src:archegonium/algae] The oldest undisputed fossil evidence of eukaryotic algae is *Bangiomorpha pubescens*, a red alga found in rocks around 1047 million years old.
[src:archegonium/algae] Recent genomic and phylogenomic approaches have significantly clarified plastid genome evolution, the horizontal movement of endosymbiont genes to the "host" nuclear genome, and plastid spread throughout the eukaryotic tree of life.
[src:archegonium/algae] It is accepted that both euglenophytes and chlorarachniophytes obtained their chloroplasts from chlorophytes that became endosymbionts.
[src:archegonium/algae] In particular, euglenophyte chloroplasts share the most resemblance with the genus *Pyramimonas*.
[src:archegonium/algae] However, there is still no clear order in which the secondary and tertiary endosymbioses occurred for the "chromist" lineages (ochrophytes, cryptophytes, haptophytes and myzozoans).
[src:archegonium/algae] Two main models have been proposed to explain the order, both of which agree that cryptophytes obtained their chloroplasts from red algae.
[src:archegonium/algae] One model, hypothesized in 2014 by John W.
[src:archegonium/algae] Stiller and coauthors, suggests that a cryptophyte became the plastid of ochrophytes, which in turn became the plastid of myzozoans and haptophytes.
[src:archegonium/algae] The other model, suggested by Andrzej Bodył and coauthors in 2009, describes that a cryptophyte became the plastid of both haptophytes and ochrophytes, and it is a haptophyte that became the plastid of myzozoans instead.
[src:archegonium/algae] These charophyte algae probably already developed filamentous thalli and holdfasts that superficially resembled plant stems and roots, and probably had an isomorphic alternation of generations.
[src:archegonium/algae] They perhaps evolved some 850 mya and might even be as early as 1 Gya during the late phase of the Boring Billion.
[src:archegonium/algae] Algaculture is a form of aquaculture involving the farming of species of algae.
[src:archegonium/algae] The majority of algae that are intentionally cultivated fall into the category of microalgae (also referred to as phytoplankton, microphytes, or planktonic algae).
[src:archegonium/algae] Global production of farmed aquatic plants, overwhelmingly dominated by seaweeds, grew in output volume from 13.5 million tonnes in 1995, to just over 30 million tonnes in 2016 and 37.8 million tonnes in 2022 and 40 million tonnes in 2024.
[src:archegonium/algae] This increase was the result of production expansions led by China, followed by Malaysia, the Philippines, the United Republic of Tanzania, and the Russian Federation.
[src:archegonium/algae] Cultured microalgae already contribute to a wide range of sectors in the emerging bioeconomy.
[src:archegonium/algae] Research suggests there are large potentials and benefits of algaculture for the development of a future healthy and sustainable food system.
[src:archegonium/algae] Seaweed farming or kelp farming is the practice of cultivating and harvesting seaweed.
[src:archegonium/algae] In its simplest form farmers gather from natural beds, while at the other extreme farmers fully control the crop's life cycle.
[src:archegonium/algae] The seven most cultivated taxa are *Eucheuma* spp., *Kappaphycus alvarezii*, *Gracilaria* spp., *Saccharina japonica*, *Undaria pinnatifida*, *Pyropia* spp., and *Sargassum fusiforme*.
[src:archegonium/algae] *Eucheuma* and *K. alvarezii* are attractive for carrageenan (a gelling agent); *Gracilaria* is farmed for agar; the rest are eaten after limited processing.
[src:archegonium/algae] Seaweeds are different from mangroves and seagrasses, as they are photosynthetic algal organisms and are non-flowering.
[src:archegonium/algae] The largest seaweed-producing countries as of 2022 are China (58.62%) and Indonesia (28.6%); followed by South Korea (5.09%) and the Philippines (4.19%).
[src:archegonium/algae] Seaweed farming has frequently been developed to improve economic conditions and to reduce fishing pressure.
[src:archegonium/algae] The Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) reported that world production in 2019 was over 35 million tonnes.
[src:archegonium/algae] North America produced some 23,000 tonnes of wet seaweed.
[src:archegonium/algae] Alaska, Maine, France, and Norway each more than doubled their seaweed production since 2018*.* As of 2019, seaweed represented 30% of marine aquaculture.
[src:archegonium/algae] In 2023, the global seaweed extract market was valued at $16.5 billion, with strong projected growth.
[src:archegonium/algae] Seaweed farming is a carbon negative crop, with a high potential for climate change mitigation.
[src:archegonium/algae] The IPCC Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate recommends "further research attention" as a mitigation tactic.
[src:archegonium/algae] World Wildlife Fund, Oceans 2050, and The Nature Conservancy publicly support expanded seaweed cultivation.
[src:archegonium/algae] An algae bioreactor is used for cultivating micro or macroalgae.
[src:archegonium/algae] Algae may be cultivated for the purposes of biomass production (as in a seaweed cultivator), wastewater treatment, CO2 fixation, or aquarium/pond filtration in the form of an algae scrubber.
[src:archegonium/algae] Algae bioreactors vary widely in design, falling broadly into two categories: open reactors and enclosed reactors.
[src:archegonium/algae] Open reactors are exposed to the atmosphere while enclosed reactors, also commonly called photobioreactors, are isolated to varying extents from the atmosphere.
[src:archegonium/algae] Specifically, algae bioreactors can be used to produce fuels such as biodiesel and bioethanol, to generate animal feed, or to reduce pollutants such as NOx and CO2 in flue gases of power plants.
[src:archegonium/algae] Fundamentally, this kind of bioreactor is based on the photosynthetic reaction, which is performed by the chlorophyll-containing algae itself using dissolved carbon dioxide and sunlight.
[src:archegonium/algae] The carbon dioxide is dispersed into the reactor fluid to make it accessible to the algae.
[src:archegonium/algae] The bioreactor has to be made out of transparent material.
[src:archegonium/algae] To be competitive and independent from fluctuating support from (local) policy on the long run, biofuels should equal or beat the cost level of fossil fuels.
[src:archegonium/algae] Here, algae-based fuels hold great promise, directly related to the potential to produce more biomass per unit area in a year than any other form of biomass.
[src:archegonium/algae] The break-even point for algae-based biofuels is estimated to occur by 2025.
[src:archegonium/algae] Today, algae are used by humans in many ways; for example, as fertilizers, soil conditioners, and livestock feed.
[src:archegonium/algae] Aquatic and microscopic species are cultured in clear tanks or ponds and are either harvested or used to treat effluents pumped through the ponds.
[src:archegonium/algae] Algaculture on a large scale is an important type of aquaculture in some places.
[src:archegonium/algae] Maerl is commonly used as a soil conditioner.
[src:archegonium/algae] Algae are used as foods in many countries: China consumes more than 70 species, including *fat choy*, a cyanobacterium considered a vegetable; Japan, over 20 species such as *nori* and *aonori*; Ireland, dulse; Chile, cochayuyo.
[src:archegonium/algae] Laver is used to make laverbread in Wales, where it is known as *bara lawr*.
[src:archegonium/algae] In Korea, green laver is used to make *gim*.
[src:archegonium/algae] The oils from some algae have high levels of unsaturated fatty acids.
[src:archegonium/algae] Some varieties of algae favored by vegetarianism and veganism contain the long-chain, essential omega-3 fatty acids, docosahexaenoic acid (DHA) and eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA).
[src:archegonium/algae] Fish oil contains the omega-3 fatty acids, but the original source is algae (microalgae in particular), which are eaten by marine life such as copepods and are passed up the food chain.
[src:archegonium/algae] The natural pigments (carotenoids and chlorophylls) produced by algae can be used as alternatives to chemical dyes and coloring agents.
[src:archegonium/algae] Carrageenan, from the red alga *Chondrus crispus*, is used as a thickener and stabilizer in milk products.
[src:archegonium/algae] Agar, a gelatinous substance derived from red algae, has a number of commercial uses.
[src:archegonium/algae] It is a good medium on which to grow bacteria and fungi, as most microorganisms cannot digest agar.
[src:archegonium/algae] Alginic acid, or alginate, is extracted from brown algae.
[src:archegonium/algae] Its uses range from gelling agents in food, to medical dressings.
[src:archegonium/algae] Alginic acid also has been used in the field of biotechnology as a biocompatible medium for cell encapsulation and cell immobilization.
[src:archegonium/algae] Molecular cuisine is also a user of the substance for its gelling properties, by which it becomes a delivery vehicle for flavours.
[src:archegonium/algae] Between 100,000 and 170,000 wet tons of *Macrocystis* are harvested annually in New Mexico for alginate extraction and abalone feed.
[src:archegonium/algae] Agricultural Research Service scientists found that 60–90% of nitrogen runoff and 70–100% of phosphorus runoff can be captured from manure effluents using a horizontal algae scrubber, also called an algal turf scrubber (ATS).
[src:archegonium/algae] Scientists developed the ATS, which consists of shallow, 30-metre (100 ft) raceways of nylon netting where algae colonies can form, and studied its efficacy for three years.
[src:archegonium/algae] They found that algae can readily be used to reduce the nutrient runoff from agricultural fields and increase the quality of water flowing into rivers, streams, and oceans.
[src:archegonium/algae] Researchers collected and dried the nutrient-rich algae from the ATS and studied its potential as an organic fertilizer.
[src:archegonium/algae] They found that cucumber and corn seedlings grew just as well using ATS organic fertilizer as they did with commercial fertilizers.
[src:archegonium/algae] Algae scrubbers, using bubbling upflow or vertical waterfall versions, are now also being used to filter aquaria and ponds.
[src:archegonium/algae] The alga *Stichococcus bacillaris* has been seen to colonize silicone resins used at archaeological sites; biodegrading the synthetic substance.
[src:archegonium/algae] Various polymers can be created from algae, which can be especially useful in the creation of bioplastics.
[src:archegonium/algae] These include hybrid plastics, cellulose-based plastics, poly-lactic acid, and bio-polyethylene.
[src:archegonium/algae] Several companies have begun to produce algae polymers commercially, including for use in flip-flops and in surf boards.
[src:archegonium/algae] Even algae is also used to prepare various polymeric resins suitable for coating applications.
[src:archegonium/algae] The third island on Kunming Lake at Beijing's Summer Palace is called Zaojian Tang Dao (藻鑒堂島).
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] A mature sporophyte produces haploid spores by meiosis, a process which reduces the number of chromosomes to half, from two sets to one.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] The resulting haploid spores germinate and grow into multicellular haploid gametophytes.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] At maturity, a gametophyte produces gametes by mitosis, the normal process of cell division in eukaryotes, which maintains the original number of chromosomes.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] Two haploid gametes (originating from different organisms of the same species or from the same organism) fuse to produce a diploid zygote, which divides repeatedly by mitosis, developing into a multicellular diploid sporophyte.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] This cycle, from gametophyte to sporophyte (or equally from sporophyte to gametophyte), is the way in which all land plants and most algae undergo sexual reproduction.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] The relationship between the sporophyte and gametophyte phases varies among different groups of plants.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] In the majority of algae, the sporophyte and gametophyte are separate independent organisms, which may or may not have a similar appearance.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] In liverworts, mosses and hornworts, the sporophyte is less well developed than the gametophyte and is largely dependent on it.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] Although moss and hornwort sporophytes can photosynthesize, they require additional photosynthate from the gametophyte to sustain growth and spore development and depend on it for supply of water, mineral nutrients and nitrogen.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] By contrast, in all modern vascular plants, the gametophyte is less well developed than the sporophyte, although their Devonian ancestors had gametophytes and sporophytes of approximately equivalent complexity.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] In ferns, the gametophyte is a small flattened autotrophic prothallus on which the young sporophyte is briefly dependent for its nutrition.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] In flowering plants, the reduction of the gametophyte is much more extreme; it consists of just a few cells which grow entirely inside the sporophyte.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] No haploid spores capable of dividing are produced, so generally there is no multicellular haploid phase.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] Some insects have a sex-determining system whereby haploid males are produced from unfertilized eggs; however the females are diploid, produced from fertilized eggs,.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] Life cycles of plants and algae with alternating haploid and diploid multicellular stages are referred to as **diplohaplontic**.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] The equivalent terms **haplodiplontic**, **diplobiontic** and **dibiontic** are also in use, as is describing such an organism as having a diphasic ontogeny.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] Life cycles of animals, in which there is only a diploid multicellular stage, are referred to as **diplontic**.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] Life cycles in which there is only a haploid multicellular stage are referred to as **haplontic**.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] Alternation of generations is defined as the alternation of multicellular diploid and haploid forms in the organism's life cycle, regardless of whether these forms are free-living.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] In some species, such as the alga *Ulva lactuca*, the diploid and haploid forms are indeed both free-living independent organisms, essentially identical in appearance and therefore said to be isomorphic.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] In many algae, the free-swimming, haploid gametes form a diploid zygote which germinates into a multicellular diploid sporophyte.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] The sporophyte produces free-swimming haploid spores by meiosis that germinate into haploid gametophytes.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] However, in land plants, either the sporophyte or the gametophyte is very much reduced and is incapable of free living.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] For example, in all bryophytes the gametophyte generation is dominant and the sporophyte is dependent on it.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] By contrast, in all seed plants the gametophytes are strongly reduced, although the fossil evidence indicates that they were derived from isomorphic ancestors.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] In seed plants, the female gametophyte develops totally within the sporophyte, which protects and nurtures it and the embryonic sporophyte that it produces.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] The pollen grains, which are the male gametophytes, are reduced to only a few cells (just three cells in many cases).
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] Here the notion of two generations is less obvious; as Bateman & Dimichele say "sporophyte and gametophyte effectively function as a single organism".
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] The alternative term 'alternation of phases' may then be more appropriate.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] Later, the phenomenon in animals became known as heterogamy, while the term "alternation of generations" was restricted to the life cycles of plants, meaning specifically the alternation of haploid gametophytes and diploid sporophytes.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] In 1851, Wilhelm Hofmeister demonstrated the morphological alternation of generations in plants, between a spore-bearing generation (sporophyte) and a gamete-bearing generation (gametophyte).
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] In 1874, Eduard Strasburger discovered the alternation between diploid and haploid nuclear phases, also called cytological alternation of nuclear phases.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] Although most often coinciding, morphological alternation and nuclear phases alternation are sometimes independent of one another, e.g., in many red algae, the same nuclear phase may correspond to two diverse morphological generations.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] In some ferns which lost sexual reproduction, there is no change in nuclear phase, but the alternation of generations is maintained.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] The diagram above shows the fundamental elements of the alternation of generations in plants.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] There are many variations in different groups of plants.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] The 'alternation of generations' in the life cycle is thus between a diploid (2*n*) generation of multicellular sporophytes and a haploid (*n*) generation of multicellular gametophytes.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] The situation is quite different from that in animals, where the fundamental process is that a multicellular diploid (2*n*) individual *directly* produces haploid (*n*) gametes by meiosis.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] In animals, spores (i.e. haploid cells which are able to undergo mitosis) are not produced, so there is no asexual multicellular generation.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] Some insects have haploid males that develop from unfertilized eggs, but the females are all diploid.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] The diagram shown above is a good representation of the life cycle of some multi-cellular algae (e.g. the genus *Cladophora*) which have sporophytes and gametophytes of almost identical appearance and which do not have different kinds of spores or gametes.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] However, there are many possible variations on the fundamental elements of a life cycle which has alternation of generations.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] Each variation may occur separately or in combination, resulting in a bewildering variety of life cycles.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] The terms used by botanists in describing these life cycles can be equally bewildering.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] There are some correlations between these variations, but they are just that, correlations, and not absolute.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] For example, in flowering plants, microspores ultimately produce microgametes (sperm) and megaspores ultimately produce megagametes (eggs).
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] However, in ferns and their allies there are groups with undifferentiated spores but differentiated gametophytes.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] For example, the fern *Ceratopteris thalictrioides* has spores of only one kind, which vary continuously in size.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] Smaller spores tend to germinate into gametophytes which produce only sperm-producing antheridia.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] Alternation of generations can take place in plants which are at once heteromorphic, sporophytic, oogametic, dioicous, heterosporic and dioecious, such as in a willow tree (as most species of the genus *Salix* are dioecious).
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] The term "plants" is taken here to mean the Archaeplastida, i.e. the glaucophytes, red and green algae and land plants.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] Alternation of generations occurs in almost all multicellular red and green algae, both freshwater forms (such as *Cladophora*) and seaweeds (such as *Ulva*).
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] In most, the generations are homomorphic (isomorphic) and free-living.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] Some species of red algae have a complex triphasic alternation of generations, in which there is a gametophyte phase and two distinct sporophyte phases.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] For further information, see Red algae: Reproduction.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] Land plants all have heteromorphic (anisomorphic) alternation of generations, in which the sporophyte and gametophyte are distinctly different.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] All bryophytes, i.e. liverworts, mosses and hornworts, have the gametophyte generation as the most conspicuous.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] As an illustration, consider a monoicous moss.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] Antheridia and archegonia develop on the mature plant (the gametophyte).
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] In the presence of water, the biflagellate sperm from the antheridia swim to the archegonia and fertilisation occurs, leading to the production of a diploid sporophyte.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] The sporophyte grows up from the archegonium.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] Its body comprises a long stalk topped by a capsule within which spore-producing cells undergo meiosis to form haploid spores.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] Most mosses rely on the wind to disperse these spores, although *Splachnum sphaericum* is entomophilous, recruiting insects to disperse its spores.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] The life cycle of ferns and their allies, including clubmosses and horsetails, the conspicuous plant observed in the field is the diploid sporophyte.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] The haploid spores develop in sori on the underside of the fronds and are dispersed by the wind (or in some cases, by floating on water).
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] If conditions are right, a spore will germinate and grow into a rather inconspicuous plant body called a prothallus.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] The haploid prothallus does not resemble the sporophyte, and as such ferns and their allies have a heteromorphic alternation of generations.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] The prothallus is short-lived, but carries out sexual reproduction, producing the diploid zygote that then grows out of the prothallus as the sporophyte.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] In the spermatophytes, the seed plants, the sporophyte is the dominant multicellular phase; the gametophytes are strongly reduced in size and very different in morphology.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] The entire gametophyte generation, with the sole exception of pollen grains (microgametophytes), is contained within the sporophyte.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] The life cycle of a dioecious flowering plant (angiosperm), the willow, has been outlined in some detail in an earlier section (A complex life cycle).
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] The life cycle of a gymnosperm is similar.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] However, flowering plants have in addition a phenomenon called 'double fertilization'.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] It has been proposed that the basis for the emergence of the diploid phase of the life cycle (sporophyte) as the dominant phase (e.g. as in vascular plants) is that diploidy allows masking of the expression of deleterious mutations through genetic complementation.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] Thus if one of the parental genomes in the diploid cells contained mutations leading to defects in one or more gene products, these deficiencies could be compensated for by the other parental genome (which nevertheless may have its own defects in other genes).
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] As the diploid phase was becoming predominant, the masking effect likely allowed genome size, and hence information content, to increase without the constraint of having to improve accuracy of DNA replication.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] The opportunity to increase information content at low cost was advantageous because it permitted new adaptations to be encoded.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] This view has been challenged, with evidence showing that selection is no more effective in the haploid than in the diploid phases of the lifecycle of mosses and angiosperms.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] Some organisms currently classified in the clade Rhizaria and thus not plants in the sense used here, exhibit alternation of generations.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] Most Foraminifera undergo a heteromorphic alternation of generations between haploid ***gamont*** and diploid ***agamont*** forms.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] The diploid form is typically much larger than the haploid form; these forms are known as the *microsphere* and *megalosphere*, respectively.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] When mycelia of different mating types meet, they produce two multinucleate ball-shaped cells, which join via a "mating bridge".
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] Nuclei move from one mycelium into the other, forming a ***heterokaryon*** (meaning "different nuclei").
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] This process is called ***plasmogamy***.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] Actual fusion to form diploid nuclei is called ***karyogamy***, and may not occur until sporangia are formed.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] Karogamy produces a diploid zygote, which is a short-lived sporophyte that soon undergoes meiosis to form haploid spores.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] When the spores germinate, they develop into new mycelia.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] The life cycle of slime moulds is very similar to that of fungi.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] Haploid spores germinate to form swarm cells or ***myxamoebae***.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] These fuse in a process referred to as *plasmogamy* and *karyogamy* to form a diploid zygote.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] The zygote develops into a plasmodium, and the mature plasmodium produces, depending on the species, one to many fruiting bodies containing haploid spores.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] Alternation between a multicellular diploid and a multicellular haploid generation is never encountered in animals.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] In some animals, there is an alternation between parthenogenic and sexually reproductive phases (heterogamy), for instance in salps and doliolids (class Thaliacea).
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] This has sometimes been called "alternation of generations", but is quite different.
[src:archegonium/alternation-of-generations] In some other animals, such as hymenopterans, males are haploid and females diploid, but this is always the case rather than there being an alternation between distinct generations.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek was the language of Homer and of fifth-century Athenian historians, playwrights, and philosophers.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] It has contributed many words to English vocabulary and has been a standard subject of study in educational institutions of the Western world since the Renaissance.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] This article primarily contains information about the Epic and Classical periods of the language, which are the best-attested periods and considered most typical of Ancient Greek.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek comprised several dialects, such as Attic, Ionic, Doric, Aeolic, and Arcadocypriot; among them, Attic Greek became the basis of Koine Greek.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Just like Koine is often included in Ancient Greek, conversely, Mycenaean Greek is usually treated separately and not always included in Ancient Greek – reflecting the fact that Greek in the first millennium BC is considered prototypical of Ancient Greek.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek was a pluricentric language, divided into many dialects.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] The main dialect groups are Attic and Ionic, Aeolic, Arcadocypriot, and Doric, many of them with several subdivisions.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Some dialects are found in standardized literary forms in literature, while others are attested only in inscriptions.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] There are also several historical forms.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Homeric Greek is a literary form of Archaic Greek (derived primarily from Ionic and Aeolic) used in the epic poems, the *Iliad* and the *Odyssey*, and in later poems by other authors.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Homeric Greek had significant differences in grammar and pronunciation from Classical Attic and other Classical-era dialects.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] The origins, early form and development of the Hellenic language family are not well understood because of a lack of contemporaneous evidence.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Several theories exist about what Hellenic dialect groups may have existed between the divergence of early Greek-like speech from the common Proto-Indo-European language and the Classical period.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] They have the same general outline but differ in some of the detail.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] The only attested dialect from this period is Mycenaean Greek, but its relationship to the historical dialects and the historical circumstances of the times imply that the overall groups already existed in some form.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Scholars assume that major Ancient Greek period dialect groups developed no later than 1120 BC, at the time of the Dorian invasions—and that their first appearances as precise alphabetic writing began in the 8th century BC.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] The invasion would not be "Dorian" unless the invaders had some cultural relationship to the historical Dorians.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] The invasion is known to have displaced population to the later Attic-Ionic regions, who regarded themselves as descendants of the population displaced by or contending with the Dorians.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] The Greeks of this period believed there were three major divisions of all Greek people – Dorians, Aeolians, and Ionians (including Athenians), each with their own defining and distinctive dialects.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Allowing for their oversight of Arcadian, an obscure mountain dialect, and Cypriot, far from the center of Greek scholarship, this division of people and language is quite similar to the results of modern archaeological-linguistic investigation.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] (Southern Italy and Sicily) in the classical period.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] West vs. non-West Greek is the strongest-marked and earliest division, with non-West in subsets of Ionic-Attic (or Attic-Ionic) and Aeolic vs.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Arcadocypriot, or Aeolic and Arcado-Cypriot vs.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Arcadocypriot apparently descended more closely from the Mycenaean Greek of the Bronze Age.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Boeotian Greek had come under a strong Northwest Greek influence, and can in some respects be considered a transitional dialect, as exemplified in the poems of the Boeotian poet Pindar who wrote in Doric with a small Aeolic admixture.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Thessalian likewise had come under Northwest Greek influence, though to a lesser degree.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Pamphylian Greek, spoken in a small area on the southwestern coast of Anatolia and little preserved in inscriptions, may be either a fifth major dialect group, or it is Mycenaean Greek overlaid by Doric, with a non-Greek native influence.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Based on the conclusions drawn by several studies and findings such as Pella curse tablet, Emilio Crespo and most scholars suggest that ancient Macedonian was a Northwest Doric dialect, which shares isoglosses with its neighboring Thessalian dialects spoken in northeastern Thessaly.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Some have also suggested an Aeolic Greek classification.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] For example, fragments of the works of the poet Sappho from the island of Lesbos are in Aeolian.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Most of the dialect sub-groups listed above had further subdivisions, generally equivalent to a city-state and its surrounding territory, or to an island.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Doric notably had several intermediate divisions as well, into Island Doric (including Cretan Doric), Southern Peloponnesus Doric (including Laconian, the dialect of Sparta), and Northern Peloponnesus Doric (including Corinthian).
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] All the groups were represented by colonies beyond Greece proper as well, and these colonies generally developed local characteristics, often under the influence of settlers or neighbors speaking different Greek dialects.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] After the conquests of Alexander the Great in the late 4th century BC, a new international dialect known as Koine or Common Greek developed, largely based on Attic Greek, but with influence from other dialects.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] This dialect slowly replaced most of the older dialects, although the Doric dialect has survived in the Tsakonian language, which is spoken in the region of modern Sparta.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Doric has also passed down its aorist terminations into most verbs of Demotic Greek.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] By about the 6th century AD, the Koine had slowly metamorphosed into Medieval Greek.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Phrygian is an extinct Indo-European language of West and Central Anatolia, which is regarded by current consensus to have been closely related to Greek.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Among Indo-European branches with living descendants, Greek is often argued to have the closest genetic ties with Armenian (see also Graeco-Armenian) and Indo-Iranian languages (see Graeco-Aryan).
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek differs from Proto-Indo-European (PIE) and other Indo-European languages in certain ways.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] In phonotactics, ancient Greek words could end only in a vowel or /n s r/; final stops were lost, as in γάλα "milk", compared with γάλακτος "of milk" (genitive).
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] The pronunciation of Ancient Greek was very different from that of Modern Greek.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek had long and short vowels; many diphthongs; double and single consonants; voiced, voiceless, and aspirated stops; and a pitch accent.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] In Modern Greek, all vowels and consonants are short.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Many vowels and diphthongs once pronounced distinctly are pronounced as /i/ (iotacism).
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Some of the stops and glides in diphthongs have become fricatives, and the pitch accent has changed to a stress accent.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Many of the changes took place in the Koine Greek period.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] The writing system of Modern Greek, however, does not reflect all pronunciation changes.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] The examples below represent Attic Greek in the 5th century BC.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Ancient pronunciation cannot be reconstructed with certainty, but Greek from the period is well documented, and there is little disagreement among linguists as to the general nature of the sounds that the letters represent.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] /oː/ raised to [uː], probably by the 4th century BC.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Greek, like all of the older Indo-European languages, is highly inflected.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] It is highly archaic in its preservation of Proto-Indo-European forms.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] In ancient Greek, nouns (including proper nouns) have five cases (nominative, genitive, dative, accusative, and vocative), three genders (masculine, feminine, and neuter), and three numbers (singular, dual, and plural).
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Verbs have four moods (indicative, imperative, subjunctive, and optative) and three voices (active, middle, and passive), as well as three persons (first, second, and third) and various other forms.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Verbs are conjugated through seven combinations of tenses and aspect (generally simply called "tenses"): the present, future, and imperfect are imperfective in aspect; the aorist, present perfect, pluperfect and future perfect are perfective in aspect.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Most tenses display all four moods and three voices, although there is no future subjunctive or imperative.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Also, there is no imperfect subjunctive, optative or imperative.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] The infinitives and participles correspond to the finite combinations of tense, aspect, and voice.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] The indicative of past tenses adds (conceptually, at least) a prefix /e-/, called the augment.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] This was probably originally a separate word, meaning something like "then", added because tenses in PIE had primarily aspectual meaning.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] The augment is added to the indicative of the aorist, imperfect, and pluperfect, but not to any of the other forms of the aorist (no other forms of the imperfect and pluperfect exist).
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] The two kinds of augment in Greek are syllabic and quantitative.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] The syllabic augment is added to stems beginning with consonants, and simply prefixes *e* (stems beginning with *r*, however, add *er*).
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Some verbs augment irregularly; the most common variation is *e* → *ei*.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] The irregularity can be explained diachronically by the loss of *s* between vowels, or that of the letter *w*, which affected the augment when it was word-initial.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] In verbs with a preposition as a prefix, the augment is placed not at the start of the word, but between the preposition and the original verb.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] For example, προσ(-)βάλλω (I attack) goes to προσ**έ**βαλoν in the aorist.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] However compound verbs consisting of a prefix that is not a preposition retain the augment at the start of the word: αὐτο(-)μολῶ goes to **ηὐ**τομόλησα in the aorist.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Following Homer's practice, the augment is sometimes not made in poetry, especially epic poetry.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] The augment sometimes substitutes for reduplication; see below.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Almost all forms of the perfect, pluperfect, and future perfect reduplicate the initial syllable of the verb stem.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Irregular duplication can be understood diachronically.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] For example, *lambanō* (root *lab*) has the perfect stem *eilēpha* (not **lelēpha*) because it was originally *slambanō*, with perfect *seslēpha*, becoming *eilēpha* through compensatory lengthening.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Reduplication is also visible in the present tense stems of certain verbs.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] These stems add a syllable consisting of the root's initial consonant followed by *i*.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] A nasal stop appears after the reduplication in some verbs.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] The earliest extant examples of ancient Greek writing (c.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] 1450 BC) are in the syllabic script Linear B.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Beginning in the 8th century BC, however, the Greek alphabet became standard, albeit with some variation among dialects.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Early texts are written in boustrophedon style, but left-to-right became standard during the classic period.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Modern editions of ancient Greek texts are usually written with accents and breathing marks, interword spacing, modern punctuation, and sometimes mixed case, but these were all introduced later.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] The beginning of Apology by Plato exemplifies Attic Greek from the Classical period of ancient Greek.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] How you, men of Athens, are feeling under the power of my accusers, I do not know: actually, even I myself almost forgot who I was because of them, they spoke so persuasively.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] And yet, loosely speaking, nothing they have said is true.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] The study of Ancient Greek in European countries in addition to Latin occupied an important place in the syllabus from the Renaissance until the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] This was true as well in the United States, where many of the nation's founders received a classically based education.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Latin was emphasized in American colleges, but Greek also was required in the colonial and early national eras, and the study of ancient Greece became increasingly popular in the mid-to-late nineteenth century, the age of American philhellenism.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] In particular, female intellectuals of the era designated the mastering of ancient Greek as essential in becoming a "woman of letters".
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is still taught as a compulsory or optional subject especially at traditional or elite schools throughout Europe, such as public schools and grammar schools in the United Kingdom.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] In 2006/07, 15,000 pupils studied ancient Greek in Germany according to the Federal Statistical Office of Germany, and 280,000 pupils studied it in Italy.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] It is a compulsory subject alongside Latin in the humanities branch of the Spanish Baccalaureate.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is taught at most major universities worldwide, often combined with Latin as part of the study of classics.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] In 2010 it was offered in three primary schools in the UK, to boost children's language skills, and was one of seven foreign languages which primary schools could teach 2014 as part of a major drive to boost education standards.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is taught as a compulsory subject in all gymnasiums and lyceums in Greece.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] It appears to have ceased in 2010, having failed to gain the recognition and acceptance of teachers.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Its first issue appeared in April 2015 as an annex to *Hebdomada Aenigmatum*.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Alfred Rahlfs included a preface, a short history of the Septuagint text, and other front matter translated into ancient Greek in his 1935 edition of the Septuagint; Robert Hanhart also included the introductory remarks to the 2006 revised Rahlfs–Hanhart edition in the language as well.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] *Akropolis World News* reports weekly a summary of the most important news in ancient Greek.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is also used by organizations and individuals, mainly Greek, who wish to denote their respect, admiration or preference for the use of this language.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] This use is sometimes considered graphical, nationalistic or humorous.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] In any case, the fact that modern Greeks can still wholly or partly understand texts written in non-archaic forms of ancient Greek shows the affinity of the modern Greek language to its ancestral predecessor.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is often used in the coinage of modern technical terms in the European languages: see English words of Greek origin.
[src:archegonium/ancient-greek] Latinized forms of ancient Greek roots are used in many of the scientific names of species and in scientific terminology.
[src:archegonium/archegonium] An **archegonium** (pl.: **archegonia**), from the Ancient Greek *ἀρχή* ("beginning") and *γόνος* ("offspring"), is a multicellular structure or organ of the gametophyte phase of certain plants, producing and containing the ovum or female gamete.
[src:archegonium/archegonium] The corresponding male organ is called the antheridium.
[src:archegonium/archegonium] The archegonium has a long neck canal or venter and a swollen base.
[src:archegonium/archegonium] Archegonia are typically located on the surface of the plant thallus, although in the hornworts they are embedded.
[src:archegonium/archegonium] In bryophytes and other cryptogams, sperm reach the archegonium by swimming in water films, whereas in Pinophyta and angiosperms, the pollen are delivered by wind or animal vectors and the sperm are delivered by means of a pollen tube.
[src:archegonium/archegonium] In the moss *Physcomitrella patens*, archegonia are not embedded but are located on top of the leafy gametophore (s.
[src:archegonium/archegonium] The Polycomb protein FIE is expressed in the unfertilized egg cell (right) as the blue colour after GUS staining reveals.
[src:archegonium/archegonium] Soon after fertilisation, the FIE gene is inactivated (the blue colour is no longer visible, left) in the young embryo.
[src:archegonium/archegonium] They are much-reduced and embedded in the megagametophytes of gymnosperms.
[src:archegonium/archegonium] The term is not used for angiosperms or the gnetophytes *Gnetum* and *Welwitschia* because the megagametophyte is reduced to just a few cells, one of which differentiates into the egg cell.
[src:archegonium/archegonium] The function of surrounding the gamete is assumed in large part by diploid cells of the megasporangium (nucellus) inside the ovule.
[src:archegonium/archegonium] Gymnosperms have their archegonium formed after pollination inside female conifer cones (megastrobili).
